Text.Value: Here, clerics may commune with their gods - and even hear their responses, if they are so favoured.
I can smell the heady smoke of the Dwarffather's forge all around you, cleric. Be welcome.
I have nothing to say to you, defiler. May the gods punish you for your transgressions against this sacred site.
It is unfortunate we live in times of battle - but I'm glad to see the Lord of War's followers grace our lowly tabernacle. Be welcome.
You are bathed in the cool gleam of moonlight. You must be a follower of Selûne.
One of the Smiling Lady's faithful graces our doorstep - we are lucky indeed. Be welcome, cleric.
You have the hawk eyes of a vigilant predator. Welcome, cleric of Helm.
Faithless creatures seldom cross our threshold, oathbreaker.
All faithful are bid entrance here, even those who serve the Queen of Chaos. Be welcome.
Fear and cruelty enter the Tabernacle. All devotion has its place here, even those who worship Lolth.
Who are you?
I feel the Platinum Dragon shining through you, cleric. Be welcome.
The smell of pine, the crunch of elder leaves. Be welcome, faithful of the Forest Queen.
Shar's faithful rarely darken our doors - but all devotion has its place here. Be welcome.
Hah - that is no surprise, holy one. You have entered the Stormshore Tabernacle.
Allow me to repay the generosity of your patron, Yondalla. Be welcome, cleric.
We are a long way from the battlefield, Gruumsh-sworn. Step lightly, but know you are welcome here.
I can feel my god's light shine brightly here - why?
I feel my god's presence in this place. Why?
I feel my god's roiling darkness in this place - why?
Ah - the merry step of a Fey faithful on our tabernacle's doorstep. Be welcome, cleric of the First Seldarine.
Be welcome, cleric of Laduguer. All faithful are accepted here, no matter their deity's proclivities.
My purpose is to connect every soul with their divine patron. How could I do that if I couldn't distinguish what deities they serve?
You have a scent of the Weave about you. I perceive you're a cleric of Mystra.
The mercy and compassion that radiate from a cleric of Ilmater are unmistakable. Welcome.
Many misunderstand the Lord of Death - but I am not one of them. Be welcome here, cleric of Kelemvor.
Your patron may not enjoy you shopping around the divine, warlock, it bothers me none. Be welcome, child of faith.
A roiling storm lies beneath your countenance. Welcome, faithful of the Destroyer.
What can I do here?
Of course, my child - within limits. Behold my wares.
A beam of morning sun enters - be welcome, cleric of Lathander.
Your very presence groans with the weight of Oghma's knowledge. Be welcome, learned one.
You have come far, I perceive. How may I serve you this day?
Are holy items available here for purchase?
Leave.
Well met, Oathsworn. Your faith may not be orthodox, but it is still welcome here.
I am Vicar Humbletoes, guardian of the Stormshore Tabernacle. I keep the peace in this sacred place and guide those in need.
Your eyes glow with fervor of one who seeks justice. You must be a priest of Tyr.
A cleric of Eilistraee enters the Tabernacle, and my heart lifts with song. Be welcome.
*News of your good deeds has travelled fast. The merchant is all too happy to extend a certain generosity towards you, where the price of goods is concerned.*
*Your notoriety precedes you. Prices have been moderated to reflect your less than welcome presence in the city.*
My, you are a long way from the Lich Queen's watchful gaze, cleric. I hope you can find some solace here, at least.
Greetings, child of faith. Be welcome to the Stormshore Tabernacle.
A returning oathbreaker. How unusual.
Welcome back, child of faith.
I see the mirthful chuckle of Garl Glittergold in those eyes of yours. Be welcome, cleric.
How did you know who I was?
I am also granted the power to provide holy resurrection through sales of revivification scrolls.

Synopsis:
Dialog between players and the temple guardian, a halfling vicar in Stormshore Tabernacle. If the player is a cleric of a particular god, the statue will tell the player that they are about to be judged by their deity. 
This dialog should give some hints to the fact that things could go badly if they acted differently from what the god defends, but should proceed to the judgement anyways.
